1. Basic Form Structure & Linking Labels
To create a form, you wrap everything in a <form> tag. Notice how the for attribute in the <label> perfectly matches the id attribute in the <input> to link them together.

HTML
<form action="/submit-data">
  <label for="username">Username:</label>
  <input type="text" id="username" name="user_name" placeholder="Enter your username">
</form>
2. Password Field & Placeholder
Using type="password" masks the characters. The placeholder gives the user a temporary hint inside the box.

HTML
<label for="pwd">Password:</label>
<input type="password" id="pwd" name="user_password" placeholder="Must be at least 8 characters">
3. Radio Buttons (Homework Solution Included)
Homework Answer: To ensure only one radio button can be selected at a time, you must give all related radio buttons the exact same name attribute (in this case, name="gender").

HTML
<p>Select your gender:</p>

<input type="radio" id="male" name="gender" value="male">
<label for="male">Male</label><br>

<input type="radio" id="female" name="gender" value="female">
<label for="female">Female</label><br>

<input type="radio" id="other" name="gender" value="other">
<label for="other">Other</label>
4. Checkboxes
Checkboxes are used when the user is allowed to select multiple options. Notice they share the same name if they belong to the same category, but they act independently.

HTML
<p>Select languages you know:</p>

<input type="checkbox" id="lang_en" name="languages" value="english">
<label for="lang_en">English</label><br>

<input type="checkbox" id="lang_hi" name="languages" value="hindi">
<label for="lang_hi">Hindi</label>
5. Dropdown Menu (Select & Option)
This creates a dropdown menu.
Homework Answer: To allow multiple selections, simply add the boolean attribute multiple to the <select> tag.  

HTML
<label for="snacks">Choose a snack:</label>
<select id="snacks" name="snack_choice" multiple>
  <option value="maggi">Maggi</option>
  <option value="kurkure">Kurkure</option>
  <option value="chips">Chips</option>
</select>
6. Textarea (Multi-line Input)
Use this for large blocks of text like addresses or feedback. You can control its default size using rows and cols.

HTML
<label for="feedback">Your Feedback:</label><br>
<textarea id="feedback" name="user_feedback" rows="5" cols="40" placeholder="Write your thoughts here..."></textarea>
7. File Upload & Date Picker
These use specific types to trigger built-in browser features (a file explorer window and a calendar popup).

HTML
<label for="dob">Date of Birth:</label>
<input type="date" id="dob" name="birthday"><br><br>

<label for="resume">Upload Resume:</label>
<input type="file" id="resume" name="user_resume">
8. Fieldset and Legend
This creates a visual grouping box around related fields, with a caption sitting on the top border.

HTML
<fieldset>
  <legend>Personal Information</legend>
  
  <label for="fname">First Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="fname" name="fname"><br><br>
  
  <label for="lname">Last Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="lname" name="lname">
</fieldset>
9. Different Ways to Create a Submit Button
Here are three different ways to submit the form data to the server.

HTML
<input type="submit" value="Submit Form">

<button type="submit">Click Here to Submit</button>

<input type="image" src="submit-arrow.png" alt="Submit" width="50" height="50">
Putting It All Together (A Complete Mini-Form)
If you copy and paste this into an HTML file, you will see a fully structured form:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<h2>User Registration</h2>

<form action="/submit-registration" method="POST">
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Account Details</legend>
    
    <label for="email">Email ID:</label>
    <input type="text" id="email" name="email" placeholder="name@example.com"><br><br>
    
    <label for="pass">Password:</label>
    <input type="password" id="pass" name="pass"><br><br>
    
    <label for="bday">Birthday:</label>
    <input type="date" id="bday" name="bday"><br><br>
    
    <input type="submit" value="Register Now">
  </fieldset>
</form>

</body>
</html>